{  
  "response_text": "The number of households engaging in social learning begins at zero across all timesteps for the first four years of the simulation. Starting at timestep 5, isolated instances of social learning emerge, with a low but steady increase observed through timestep 20. By timesteps 21–25, there is a notable acceleration in adoption, reaching peaks of 50–54 households by timesteps 27–29. The data reveals two pronounced plateaus: one around timestep 15 (15–18 households) and another between timesteps 23–25 (20–25 households). The final state of the system shows a near-doubling of social learning participation compared to its mid-simulation levels. This pattern suggests a gradual diffusion of social learning practices within the population, potentially driven by environmental pressures or adaptive behavioral adjustments, even under constraints that theoretically limit direct strategy switching. The non-linear escalation in social learning could reflect accumulating resource competition or climatic variability prompting information-sharing behaviors despite homogenized behavioral type assignments. Early stabilization (timesteps 1–5) gives way to dynamic shifts, with the most significant changes occurring in the later simulation phases."
}

